    "whySwitch": "Heroku was the prototype for developer-friendly PaaS. Then Salesforce bought it, axed the free tier in November 2022, raised prices, and in late 2024 announced it had entered 'sustaining engineering' mode — meaning no new features, only critical security patches, and eventual wind-down. If you stayed for the convenience, you're now paying Heroku prices for a platform in maintenance-only mode with no roadmap.\n\nVercel and Netlify filled the frontend gap but introduced their own pressure: bandwidth overages on Netlify can generate unexpected bills on a popular post, and Vercel's function execution and bandwidth charges scale uncomfortably fast past their free tier. Render is the closest Heroku successor in feel, but its usage-based pricing climbs steeply once you move beyond hobby workloads.\n\nThe self-hosted alternatives in this category let you run an equivalent platform on hardware you control — often a single VPS or a spare machine at home. The cost ceiling is your server bill, not a metered usage dial.",
